//GOD1PRF:800282 Next, let $L^{\prime}$ be the subring of $L$ generated by $K$ and $X_{1}, \ldots, X_{n}$. Since $L^{\prime}$ contains K and $\mathrm{X}_{1}, \ldots, \mathrm{X}_{n-1}$, it contains $\mathrm{K}^{\prime}$; and since it contains $\mathrm{K}^{\prime}$ and $\mathrm{X}_{n}$, it contains L . Hence $L^{\prime}=L$, and therefore (PR 3) is satisfied.
claim h_s27_construction_PR3 :
