claim h_s31_l6_statement :
  coprime_elements K add mul
    (ring_nat_power K add mul (p i) (r i))
    (ring_nat_power K add mul (p j) (r j)).
admit.
//GOD1PRF:962777 Let us first prove Lemma 6. Let $d$ be a common divisor of $b_{i}$ and $b_{j}$, where $i \neq j$. If $d$ is not a unit, then $d$ has a prime divisor $p$, which therefore divides both $b_{i}$ and $b_{j}$; but if $p$ divides
claim h_s31_l6_common_divisor_unit : forall d :e K,
  ring_divides K mul d (ring_nat_power K add mul (p i) (r i)) ->
  ring_divides K mul d (ring_nat_power K add mul (p j) (r j)) ->
  ring_unit K add mul d.
admit.
//GOD1PRF:963048 it divides $p_{i}$ and is therefore an associate of $p_{i}$. Hence, if $b_{i}$ and $b_{j}$ are not coprime, there is an extremal element $p \in \mathrm{~K}$ which is an associate of both $p_{i}$ and $p_{j}$, and this contradicts the hypothesis that $p_{i}$ and $p_{j}$ are not associates if $i \neq j$. This proves Lemma 6.
claim h_s31_l6_conclusion :
  coprime_elements K add mul
